vectorData.altText: 12. The _________ ___________ ___________ forms the floor of the anterior recesses of the ischioanal fossae.
22A   The Anterior Recesses of the Ischioanal Fossae
The ischioanal fossae of the anal triangle extend into the urogenital triangle superior to the deep perineal pouch and perineal membrane. These are the anterior recesses of the ischioanal fossae.

Look at Figure C and confirm the following: 
The floors of the anterior recesses are the deep perineal pouch. 
The lateral walls of the anterior recesses are the obturator internis muscle.
The medial walls of the anterior recesses are the levator ani. 
The anterior recesses of the ischioanal fossae are  dead-end spaces that end at the pubis, to which both the perineal membrane and the levator ani attach.
Realize that the anterior recesses are extensions of the ischioanal fossae; these spaces are continuous with each other and filled with fat. They also, however contain important neurovascular elements that serve perineal structures.
